{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584777"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:57:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:57:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14803"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14803"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.13,0.58,0.18,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7494"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58685"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7494"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14803"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44089"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7660"},{"type":"tags","id":"7871"},{"type":"tags","id":"7873"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18337"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18575"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58685"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most accurate regarding aplastic anaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Only two cell lineages are affected","The bone marrow shows increased cellularity","There is a deficiency of white blood cells.","Only red blood cells and platelets are affected","The bone marrow shows normal cellularity with dysmegakaryopoiesis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAplastic anaemia is characterised by pancytopenia (reduction in all three major blood cell lineages) and a hypocellular bone marrow. The clinical presentation typically includes symptoms related to each affected cell line: anaemia (fatigue), neutropenia (infections), and thrombocytopenia (bleeding).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll three major blood cell lineages are affected\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. By definition, aplastic anaemia involves pancytopenia, affecting erythrocytes, leukocytes, and platelets. This explains the patient\u0027s presentation with fatigue (anaemia), oral ulcers (neutropenia), and petechiae (thrombocytopenia).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly two cell lineages are affected\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Bicytopenia may occur in other conditions but is not consistent with aplastic anaemia, which affects all three major cell lines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe bone marrow shows increased cellularity\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. In aplastic anaemia, the bone marrow is characteristically hypocellular with fatty replacement of the normal haematopoietic tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly red blood cells and platelets are affected\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. This pattern would be more consistent with other conditions such as myelodysplastic syndrome, but not aplastic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe bone marrow shows normal cellularity with dysmegakaryopoiesis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. This finding would be more consistent with immune thrombocytopenia or myelodysplastic syndrome. Aplastic anaemia shows marked hypocellularity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of aplastic anaemia requires both peripheral blood pancytopenia and bone marrow hypocellularity. The condition can be inherited but is more commonly acquired, with potential triggers including medications, chemicals, radiation, viral infections, or autoimmune processes. Treatment options include supportive care, immunosuppression, and haematopoietic stem cell transplantation in appropriate candidates.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aplastic anaemia affects all three major blood cell lineages (pancytopenia).","Bone marrow biopsy in aplastic anaemia shows hypocellular marrow with fatty replacement.","The diagnosis requires both peripheral pancytopenia and bone marrow hypocellularity."],"references":["Frisch, B., \u0026 Bartl, R. (2012). Atlas of bone marrow pathology (Vol. 15). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media","Porwit, A., McCullough, J., \u0026 Erber, W. N. (2011). Blood and bone marrow pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Moore CA, Krishnan K. Aplastic Anemia. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534212/","Kulasekararaj A, Cavenagh J, Dokal I, Foukaneli T, Gandhi S, Garg M, Griffin M, Hillmen P, Ireland R, Killick S, Mansour S, Mufti G, Potter V, Snowden J, Stanworth S, Zuha R, Marsh J; BSH Committee. Guidelines for the diagnosis and management of adult aplastic anaemia: A British Society for Haematology Guideline. Br J Haematol. 2024 Mar;204(3):784-804. doi: 10.1111/bjh.19236. Epub 2024 Jan 21. PMID: 38247114."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44089"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14803"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44089"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-02T17:02:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-05T19:48:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7494"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58685"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","i